Orchestrates the three CLI-facing scan operations — full scan, staleness check, and incremental update — by composing `ctx-summarize`'s leaf/rollup summarization with this crate's directory walker, hash-tree tracking, and README writer.

`load_prompts` deliberately resolves `prompts_dir` against the process cwd, not the scan target `base` — CTX's own prompt files live outside whatever directory is being scanned. `summarize` is the shared inner step, generic over `Fs`/`Agent` so tests can substitute in-memory fakes; it calls `summ::scope_check` before doing any work, meaning large target sets can be rejected before any model call unless `approve` is set.

`scan_run` always summarizes everything and writes fresh hash sidecars afterward via `hash::store`. `check_run` never touches the model or writes anything — pure read/diff, safe to call anywhere, returning a `Staleness` report. `update_run` is check-then-regenerate: it computes and diffs hashes first, short-circuits with no writes at all if `stale.is_fresh()`, and otherwise loads prompts, calls the private `regenerate`, persists the new hash tree, and rewrites the README — meaning a fresh tree does zero I/O beyond the walk and hash compute.

`regenerate` processes staleness in a specific fixed order: changed leaves first (via `summ::summarize_leaf`), then orphan leaf files removed via `fs.remove`, then stale directory rollups last — relying on `stale.stale_dirs` already being sorted deepest-first by `hash::diff` so parent rollups see up-to-date child summaries. It also re-applies `scope_check` against just the changed-file count, independent of the check in `summarize`.

Depends on `ctx_summarize::runner` for the actual leaf/rollup summarization logic and `Prompts` loading, and on sibling modules `hash`, `readme`, `walker`, `error` within this crate for the tree-hashing, README generation, directory walk, and error types respectively — this file only orchestrates their call order.